A message from our friends at High Point Swim Club:

High Point Swim Club offers comprehensive swimming instruction to a wide range of ability levels.

Call 336-887-4713 or visit them on the web at highpointswimclub.org. HPSC follows CDC & NCDHHS COVID-19 guidelines and protocols.

· Lessons for children ages 3 and older are offered throughout the day and on your schedule. Group lessons are offered afterschool with 2:1 student to teacher ratios

· Need a place to have a unique birthday party? Host your next special day with up to 20 of your friends at a glow stick swim party.

Aaron Reeves, MS

CEO - Head Coach - High Point Swim Club - ASCA Level 4
US Mail: PO Box 5815 High Point NC 27262
Igloo: 1705 Whitehall High Point, NC 27262
Phone: (mobile) 336-253-3737 (pool) 336.887.4772 (direct) 336.887.4710
Club Website: www.highpointswimclub.org

post_text:
A message from our friends at Soccer Shots:

We are so excited to announce that we offer community-based programs, while we are not able to run Soccer Shots at your school this Fall. Our Fall season kicks off the week of 9/8 (Monday locations start 9/14), and we offer sessions for children ages 2-8. Click here to view our complete list of available public park programs.

Did you know that we also offer private neighborhood programs? These neighborhood sessions can be structured as a week-long camp or weekly sessions. They can take place in your own backyard with your neighborhood, family, and friends, and we can schedule it for a day and time that works best for you! Click here for more information and to sign up to become a neighborhood host!

We cannot wait to return to your school, and until then we hope you'll join us on Soccer Island at one of our community-based programs!

Thanks,

The Soccer Shots GSO Team
gso@soccershots.org
336.451.7503
soccershots.org/gso

In an effort to support the people and communities most affected by COVID-19, we have committed to donating over 600,000 Dial soap products to FEMA Federal Emergency Management Agency, supporting their mission to help people during disasters.

More than ever, we need to take care of each other, so show us your #IWashMyHandsFor pictures to show just how powerful our hands 🙌 can be.

Share your support by:
✋ writing on your hand
🗒 using a sticky note
🖊 tracing your hands

For a chance to be featured, be sure to:
1️⃣ Tag @Dial
2️⃣ Make the post public
3️⃣ Nominate a friend to post too!

post_text:
Teacher and Staff Appreciation Week

This week is National Teacher Appreciation Week! We cannot celebrate our teachers and staff in the way we are used to right now, but we can do it virtually!

Monday (Say Thanks) – Send a teacher or a staff member a note of thanks via email

Tuesday (Share Smiles) – Make a teacher or staff member smile or laugh with a picture or video message

Wednesday (Send Gifts) – Give a teacher or staff member a digital gift card (Amazon has them starting at $1)

Thursday (Sing Praises) – Share an inspirational song or create art for a teacher or staff member.

Friday (Spread Love) – Use social media to give a positive shout-out to teachers and staff members!

If you need a staff member's email, please email Emily Vaughn @evaughn@pahp.com. I am happy to give you emails of teachers, front staff, office, assistants and others. Thank you for helping us celebrate our teachers and staff that have worked so hard through this pandemic!

post_text:
Shout Out!🥳
Great Job!!

Mr. Armentrout, Mr. Howell, Mrs. Turner, Ms. Griffith, Mr. Rodriguez, and Mrs. Dicey

Hi Mrs. Norcross,

I hope you are well! I wanted to tell you that Noah had such a wonderful experience in 6th grade. He is new to Phoenix and we were both unsure of what to expect but it has been such a positive experience. He loves school and loves to learn and having 6th grade cut short has been difficult for him. I want to also tell you that his teachers, Mr. Armentrout, Mr. Howell, Mrs. Turner, Ms. Griffith, Mr. Rodriguez, and Mrs. Dicey have made the transition to home learning smooth and clear. Their support has been endless and if he or I have questions, they are just a click away!
I really appreciate their organized assignments and consistent communication.
He is really looking forward to 7th grade and we hope school will resume in August.
Stay safe and be well!

Sincerely,
Melissa Tenney

post_text:
Hi Phoenix Families! Next week we will be hosting an AT HOME SPIRIT WEEK! Each day you can upload a photo to our Facebook Page and the post with the largest number of likes will win! (This is optional. Please do not feel pressure to participate if it causes added stress.)

Monday – Cutest Pet Day - Send us pictures of your pets! (You can dress them up)

Tuesdays – Tiktok Tuesday – Send us a TikTok video or a funny video with your family. We want to see your creativity!

Wednesday – Creativity Wednesday – Show us something creative you’ve been doing! Sidewalk Chalk Art, Painting, etc.

Thursday – Super Hero Thursday – Dress up as your favorite Super Hero! (remember these days our superheroes are doctors, nurses, delivery drivers and all the others out there keeping everything going so we can stay healthy!)

Friday - Pajama Day. Stay in your PJ’s all day!

Wide Open School

Scholastic
April 1 at 2:03 PM ·

With millions of students out of school, the struggles of making distance learning work for all kids is more important than ever. That’s why we joined a coalition to launch WideOpenSchool.org, a new site to support families and educators who are transitioning to remote learning as a result of the coronavirus. Wide Open School is a free and open collection of the best learning experiences and activities including #ScholasticLearnAtHome for kids curated by the editors at Common Sense Media and organized by grade band and subject.

You are doing a great job as an administrator.

This will pass soon.

Rahul Zode

From our Istation Representative :

Istation’s online home resources are available for schools using Istation for reading, math, and/or Spanish literacy. Istation’s home component includes resources for students and parents. Students have access to hundreds of learning activities, including digital books, printable books, math games, and more. Students can use Istation outside the school on PCs, Macs, laptops, or tablet devices, including Android tablets, iPads, and Amazon Fires.

Parents have access to Istation’s Parent Portal, which provides skill-building lessons that parents can go over with their child and includes printable materials for use at home. The Parent Portal can be accessed on any device with a browser, such as a smartphone, tablet, or PC.

I am including a helpful document for your teachers, including instructions on how to get started, and how to help parents. If you have additional questions or need help with anything, just let me know.

Istation Home- Click here for more information

Phoenix Academy Parents and Families! We’re only ONE WEEK AWAY from kicking off the Phoenix Academy Fun Run and Color Run and PLEDGING IS NOW OPEN!

Register online at FUNRUN.COM and start getting pledges! Next Tuesday our 2-week fundraising program will officially begin on campus, and we’re so excited! We’ll start with a Pep Rally, and then your family will gather pledges and enter them on FUNRUN.COM. At the end, every student will participate in the Phoenix Academy Fun Run and Color Run!

This year, our goal is to raise $30,000 for technology, and we need your help! Please begin thinking about friends and family who could pledge your student for the Phoenix Academy Fun Run and Color Run.

Look for a Pledgebook to come home on March 17th with more information. And don’t forget to save the Fun Run Date—March 26th—on your calendar. You’re invited to come out and cheer on our students! More details to come. Thank you for supporting Phoenix Academy!

post_text:
Dr. Ben Carson has one of the most prolific success stories in modern medicine. Born into poverty, he eventually became one of the most prominent neurological surgeons in the United States; having performed the first successful separation of Siamese twins. He is also the author of a series of best-selling books, and after retiring from practicing medicine in 2013, he ran for a bid for the White House in 2015.

He currently serves as the secretary for the US Department of Housing and Urban Development. #PAHP #BlackHistoryMonth

Agricultural scientist George Washington Carver (1860s-1943) was the most prominent African-American scientist of the 20th century. He made many products using peanuts, but also used sweet potatoes and soybeans for his inventions as well.

Among the many peanut-based products he made were medicines such as antiseptics, laxatives, and goiter (neck swelling) medications. #PAHP #BlackHistoryMonth

post_text:
Tomorrow marks the beginning of Black History Month, which actually got its start here in the Triad.

The Greensboro sit-ins started at a lunch counter in a former downtown Woolworth store 60 years ago this month, and are a turning point in the civil rights movement. Clarence Henderson (pictured below) is one of the participants of this movement for racial equality.

Today, what was once the Greensboro location for Woolworth is now the International Civil Rights Center and Museum. #BlackHistoryMonth
